# Code Writing Style Rules

## Function Definitions

- Prefer arrow functions over function declarations for variable assignments
- Always use const for function assignments (never let or var)
- For a **single-expression** body (including one JSX tree), use an **implicit return** — `(expr)` when the expression spans multiple lines — not `{ return expr; }`. Use a block body only for multiple statements or locals before the value.

```tsx
// Good
items.map((item) => (
    <SelectItem key={item.value} value={item.value}>
        {item.label}
    </SelectItem>
));

// Bad
items.map((item) => {
    return (
        <SelectItem key={item.value} value={item.value}>
            {item.label}
        </SelectItem>
    );
});
```

## Control Flow

- Prefer early returns over nested conditionals
- Use guard clauses to exit functions early when validation fails or conditions aren't met
- Structure functions with early returns: validate inputs first, then process logic
- Avoid deep nesting by returning early on error conditions or invalid states

```javascript
// Good
const processUser = (user) => {
    if (!user) return null;
    if (!user.email) return null;
    return { id: user.id, email: user.email.toLowerCase() };
};

// Bad
const processUser = (user) => {
    if (user) {
        if (user.email) {
            return { id: user.id, email: user.email.toLowerCase() };
        }
    }
    return null;
};
```

## Conditionals and booleans

- Branch on **truthiness** (`if (x)`, `x ? a : b`, `!x`) when you only care whether a value is usable — not `x != null` or explicit null/undefined checks unless `0`, `''`, or `false` must be treated separately from missing (then use `??` or explicit null/undefined checks).
- When you need a **`boolean` primitive** (props, return types), use **`!!value`** — not `Boolean(value)`. In `if` / ternaries that only branch on "has a value", you usually need neither `!!` nor `Boolean`.

```javascript
// Good
if (user.email) send(user.email);
const label = lead.source ? map[lead.source] : '—';
const hasErrors = !!errors.length;

// Bad (unless falsy values are valid data)
if (user.email != null) send(user.email);
const hasErrors = Boolean(errors.length);
```

## Array Iteration

- Prefer `array.forEach((item) => { ... })` over `for (const item of array) { ... }`
- Use forEach for side effects and iteration over arrays
- Reserve for...of loops for cases where early break/continue is needed

```javascript
// Good
items.forEach((item) => updateItem(item));

// Bad (unless you need break/continue)
for (const item of items) {
    updateItem(item);
}
```

## Variable Naming

- Avoid variable abbreviations - use full, descriptive words
- Prefer clarity over brevity in variable names
- Use complete words that clearly express the variable's purpose

```javascript
// Good
const handleUser = (user) => {
    if (!user) return null;
    return user.name;
};

// Bad
const handleUser = (usr) => {
    if (!usr) return null;
    return usr.name;
};
```

## Documentation

- Include JSDoc comments for all exported functions and complex internal functions
- Document function parameters, return values, and any side effects
- Update documentation when function signatures or behavior changes
- Use @param, @returns, and @example tags for comprehensive documentation
- **Always** use a multi-line JSDoc block — never a single-line `/** … */` comment, even for short descriptions

```javascript
// Good
/**
 * Returns the display label for a lead source.
 */
const getSourceLabel = (source) => { ... };

// Bad
/** Returns the display label for a lead source. */
const getSourceLabel = (source) => { ... };
```

## ESLint

- **Never** add ESLint suppressions: no `eslint-disable`, `eslint-disable-next-line`, `eslint-disable-line`, or file-level `/* eslint-disable … */` comments.
- If a rule fires, **fix the code** (refactor, types, imports, hook deps, etc.) or adjust project config in an agreed change — do not silence the linter in source.

## Preserve existing comments

- Do not delete or strip existing comments as part of an unrelated edit (e.g. refactoring, logging changes, formatting). If the comment still describes the code correctly, keep it.
- Only remove or rewrite a comment when the behavior it describes has actually changed, or when it is clearly wrong or redundant with adjacent code.
- Restoring accidentally removed comments is preferred over leaving the code comment-free.
